======================================================================
PART 1: Z[omega] NORM SPECTRUM — ACHIEVABLE NORMS
======================================================================

N(a + b*omega) = a^2 - a*b + b^2
This is a positive definite quadratic form (discriminant -3)

Which positive integers are representable as a^2 - ab + b^2?
Answer: n is representable iff all prime factors p = 2 mod 3 appear
with EVEN exponent. Equivalently: n has no prime factor = 2 mod 3
with odd exponent.

Representable norms up to 100: [1, 3, 4, 7, 9, 12, 13, 16, 19, 21, 25, 27, 28, 31, 36, 37, 39, 43, 48, 49, 52, 57, 61, 63, 64, 67, 73, 75, 76, 79, 81, 84, 91, 93, 97, 100]
Non-representable: [2, 5, 6, 8, 10, 11, 14, 15, 17, 18, 20, 22, 23, 24, 26, 29, 30, 32, 33, 34, 35, 38, 40, 41, 42, 44, 45, 46, 47, 50, 51, 53, 54, 55, 56, 58, 59, 60, 62, 65, 66, 68, 69, 70, 71, 72, 74, 77, 78, 80, 82, 83, 85, 86, 87, 88, 89, 90, 92, 94, 95, 96, 98, 99]

Primes = 2 mod 3 up to 100: [2, 5, 11, 17, 23, 29, 41, 47, 53, 59, 71, 83, 89]

Note: the Eisenstein norm for tournaments is NOT the standard norm.
Tournament norm: N(I(omega)) = a1^2 - a1*a2 + a2^2 - a1 - a2 + 1
                             = N_std(a1 - (a2+1)/2, ...) - shifted
Let's check which TOURNAMENT norms occur:
  Achieved tournament norms: [1, 3, 13, 21, 25, 31, 43, 52, 57, 64, 73, 100, 111, 121, 133, 139, 144, 147, 157, 169, 211, 217, 225, 241, 259, 273, 307, 324, 327, 343]...
  Total distinct norms: 153
  Gap norms (not achieved): [2, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10, 11, 12, 14, 15, 16, 17, 18, 19, 20, 22, 23, 24, 26, 27, 28, 29, 30, 32, 33, 34, 35, 36]...

  Tournament norms mod 3: {0: 45, 1: 108}
  NO norm = 2 mod 3? True

======================================================================
PART 2: I(omega) MOD 3 — THE REDUCED INVARIANT
======================================================================

I(omega) = (1-a2) + (a1-a2)*omega in Z[omega]
Reducing mod 3:
  I(omega) mod 3 = ((1-a2) mod 3) + ((a1-a2) mod 3)*omega
  Lives in F_9 = F_3[omega] = (Z/3Z)[x]/(x^2+x+1)

I(omega) mod 3 distribution at n=7 (5000 samples):
  0 + 0*omega :  508 ( 10.2%), norm mod 3 = 0
  0 + 1*omega :  474 (  9.5%), norm mod 3 = 1
  0 + 2*omega :  654 ( 13.1%), norm mod 3 = 1
  1 + 0*omega :  686 ( 13.7%), norm mod 3 = 1
  1 + 1*omega :  588 ( 11.8%), norm mod 3 = 1
  1 + 2*omega :  428 (  8.6%), norm mod 3 = 0
  2 + 0*omega :  519 ( 10.4%), norm mod 3 = 1
  2 + 1*omega :  502 ( 10.0%), norm mod 3 = 0
  2 + 2*omega :  641 ( 12.8%), norm mod 3 = 1

F_9 has 9 elements, but only some appear as I(omega) mod 3.
The non-appearing elements correspond to 'forbidden residues'.

All 9 elements of F_9 = F_3[omega]:
  0 + 0*omega: norm = 0, occurs 508 times
  0 + 1*omega: norm = 1, occurs 474 times
  0 + 2*omega: norm = 1, occurs 654 times
  1 + 0*omega: norm = 1, occurs 686 times
  1 + 1*omega: norm = 1, occurs 588 times
  1 + 2*omega: norm = 0, occurs 428 times
  2 + 0*omega: norm = 1, occurs 519 times
  2 + 1*omega: norm = 0, occurs 502 times
  2 + 2*omega: norm = 1, occurs 641 times

======================================================================
PART 3: I(i) — EVALUATION AT 4TH ROOT OF UNITY (GAUSSIAN)
======================================================================

I(i) = 1 + a1*i + a2*i^2 = 1 + a1*i - a2 = (1-a2) + a1*i
This is a Gaussian integer in Z[i]!
Gaussian norm: N(I(i)) = (1-a2)^2 + a1^2

Gaussian norm distribution at n=7 (3000 samples):
  N_gauss =      1:    7 (  0.2%)
  N_gauss =      2:   13 (  0.4%)
  N_gauss =      4:    1 (  0.0%)
  N_gauss =      5:   25 (  0.8%)
  N_gauss =     10:    3 (  0.1%)
  N_gauss =     17:   33 (  1.1%)
  N_gauss =     26:   30 (  1.0%)
  N_gauss =     36:   15 (  0.5%)
  N_gauss =     37:   16 (  0.5%)
  N_gauss =     50:   45 (  1.5%)
  N_gauss =     65:   16 (  0.5%)
  N_gauss =     81:   28 (  0.9%)
  N_gauss =     82:   36 (  1.2%)
  N_gauss =     85:    4 (  0.1%)
  N_gauss =    101:   32 (  1.1%)
  N_gauss =    121:   13 (  0.4%)
  N_gauss =    122:   30 (  1.0%)
  N_gauss =    144:   34 (  1.1%)
  N_gauss =    145:   58 (  1.9%)
  N_gauss =    169:   29 (  1.0%)

Comparison: Eisenstein vs Gaussian norm
    a1   a2     H  N_eis  N_gau N_eis/N_gau
    36    6    97   1075   1321     0.8138
    37    4    91   1197   1378     0.8687
    45    6   115   1741   2050     0.8493
    28    4    73    657    793     0.8285
    32    4    81    877   1033     0.8490
    25    5    71    496    641     0.7738
    34    6    93    949   1181     0.8036
    30    4    77    763    909     0.8394
    28    6    81    619    809     0.7651
    30    3    73    787    904     0.8706
    13    0    27    157    170     0.9235
    53    8   139   2389   2858     0.8359
    20    1    45    361    400     0.9025
    24    4    65    469    585     0.8017
     9    1    23     64     81     0.7901

Relation between the two norms:
  N_eis = a1^2 - a1*a2 + a2^2 - a1 - a2 + 1
  N_gau = a1^2 + (1-a2)^2 = a1^2 + a2^2 - 2*a2 + 1
  Difference: N_eis - N_gau = -a1*a2 + 2*a2^2 - a1 + a2
            = a2*(2*a2 - a1) - (a1 - a2)
            = (a2 - 1)*(2*a2 - a1) + (a2 - a1)

  N_eis = N_gau iff -a1*a2 + 2*a2^2 - a1 + a2 = 0
                iff a2*(2*a2 - a1 + 1) = a1
  For a2=0: a1=0 (trivial)
  For a2=1: 1*(2 - a1 + 1) = a1 => 3 - a1 = a1 => a1 = 3/2 (no integer)
  So they are equal ONLY at (0,0) among non-negative integers!

======================================================================
PART 4: I(zeta_8) — 8TH ROOT OF UNITY EVALUATION
======================================================================

zeta_8 = e^(2*pi*i/8) = cos(pi/4) + i*sin(pi/4) = (1+i)/sqrt(2)
       = (0.7071067811865476+0.7071067811865476j)
  |zeta_8| = 1
  zeta_8^2 = i
  zeta_8^4 = -1
  zeta_8^8 = 1

I(zeta_8) = 1 + a1*zeta_8 + a2*zeta_8^2 = 1 + a1*zeta_8 + a2*i
  Real part: 1 + a1*cos(pi/4) = 1 + a1/sqrt(2)
  Imag part: a1*sin(pi/4) + a2 = a1/sqrt(2) + a2

  Z[zeta_8] has rank phi(8) = 4 as Z-module
  Basis: 1, zeta_8, zeta_8^2=i, zeta_8^3 = i*zeta_8
  I(zeta_8) = 1 + a1*zeta_8 + a2*zeta_8^2
  Only uses 3 of the 4 basis elements (no zeta_8^3 component)

Norm in Z[zeta_8]: N(alpha) = |alpha|^2 * |sigma(alpha)|^2
  where sigma is the Galois conjugation zeta_8 -> zeta_8^3
  sigma(I(zeta_8)) = 1 + a1*zeta_8^3 + a2*zeta_8^6
                   = 1 + a1*zeta_8^3 + a2*(-i)

  Sample |I(zeta_8)|^2 values at n=7:
    a1= 22, a2= 5: |I(zeta_8)|^2 = 696.68, full norm = 225252
    a1= 33, a2= 6: |I(zeta_8)|^2 = 1452.68, full norm = 1161154
    a1= 46, a2= 6: |I(zeta_8)|^2 = 2608.38, full norm = 4428041
    a1= 19, a2= 1: |I(zeta_8)|^2 = 416.74, full norm = 128881
    a1= 18, a2= 2: |I(zeta_8)|^2 = 405.37, full norm = 102409
    a1= 36, a2= 5: |I(zeta_8)|^2 = 1627.47, full norm = 1654372
    a1= 26, a2= 4: |I(zeta_8)|^2 = 876.85, full norm = 446449
    a1= 49, a2= 8: |I(zeta_8)|^2 = 3089.67, full norm = 5692194
    a1= 22, a2= 2: |I(zeta_8)|^2 = 582.34, full norm = 230409
    a1= 36, a2= 4: |I(zeta_8)|^2 = 1567.56, full norm = 1659169

  |I(zeta_8)|^2 = (1 + a1/sqrt(2))^2 + (a1/sqrt(2) + a2)^2
  = 1 + a1*sqrt(2) + a1^2/2 + a1^2/2 + a1*a2*sqrt(2) + a2^2
  = 1 + a1^2 + a2^2 + (a1 + a1*a2)*sqrt(2)
  NOTE: this has an IRRATIONAL part (involving sqrt(2))!
  So |I(zeta_8)|^2 is NOT in Z unless a1*(1+a2) = 0
  i.e., a1=0 or a2=-1 (impossible since a2>=0)
  So only for trivial a1=0, |I(zeta_8)|^2 is rational!

