======================================================================
PART 6: QUATERNIONIC STRUCTURE OF I(i)
======================================================================

I(i) = (1-a2) + a1*i = Gaussian integer
Gaussian integers Z[i] are the 'complex part' of quaternions H

Can we define a 'quaternionic tournament invariant'?
  Q(T) = I(1) + I(i)*j = (1+a1+a2) + ((1-a2) + a1*i)*j
  = (1+a1+a2) + (1-a2)*j + a1*ij
  = (1+a1+a2) + (1-a2)*j + a1*k
  (using quaternion convention ij = k)

Quaternionic tournament invariant Q(T) = w + xi + yj + zk:
  a1= 22, a2= 5: Q = 28 + 0i + -4j + 22k, |Q|^2 = 1284, H = 65
  a1= 33, a2= 6: Q = 40 + 0i + -5j + 33k, |Q|^2 = 2714, H = 91
  a1= 46, a2= 6: Q = 53 + 0i + -5j + 46k, |Q|^2 = 4950, H = 117
  a1= 19, a2= 1: Q = 21 + 0i + 0j + 19k, |Q|^2 = 802, H = 43
  a1= 18, a2= 2: Q = 21 + 0i + -1j + 18k, |Q|^2 = 766, H = 45
  a1= 36, a2= 5: Q = 42 + 0i + -4j + 36k, |Q|^2 = 3076, H = 93
  a1= 26, a2= 4: Q = 31 + 0i + -3j + 26k, |Q|^2 = 1646, H = 69
  a1= 49, a2= 8: Q = 58 + 0i + -7j + 49k, |Q|^2 = 5814, H = 131
  a1= 22, a2= 2: Q = 25 + 0i + -1j + 22k, |Q|^2 = 1110, H = 53
  a1= 36, a2= 4: Q = 41 + 0i + -3j + 36k, |Q|^2 = 2986, H = 89

Quaternionic norm |Q|^2 = (1+a1+a2)^2 + (1-a2)^2 + a1^2
  = I(1)^2 + N_gaussian(I(i))
  = (total indep sets + 1)^2 + Gaussian norm

Relation to H:
  H = I(2) = 1 + 2*a1 + 4*a2
  I(1) = 1 + a1 + a2
  N_gau = a1^2 + (1-a2)^2
  |Q|^2 = I(1)^2 + N_gau = (1+a1+a2)^2 + a1^2 + (1-a2)^2

  Can we recover H from |Q|^2? Probably not uniquely,
  but |Q|^2 encodes STRICTLY MORE information than H.

Octonionic extension (dim 8 = 2^3):
  Would need evaluations at 4 independent points to fill 8 components
  e.g., I(1), I(i), I(omega), I(omega*i)
  But I(x) is degree 2, so 3 points determine it completely
  An octonionic invariant would be REDUNDANT for quadratic I(x)
  This is why n=7 (quadratic I.P.) doesn't 'see' the octonionic structure
  At n>=8, I(x) can be cubic => need 4 points => octonionic NOT redundant!
  THIS is the Cayley-Dickson connection: at n=8, the invariant
  needs more than quaternionic (dim 4) structure!

======================================================================
PART 7: THE FOUR EVALUATIONS I(1), I(2), I(omega), I(i)
======================================================================

I(x) = 1 + a1*x + a2*x^2 (degree 2)
Three points determine I(x) uniquely.
With FOUR points, we have one redundancy = one CHECK.

The four evaluations:
  I(1) = 1 + a1 + a2         (total independent sets + empty set)
  I(2) = 1 + 2*a1 + 4*a2     (= H, Hamiltonian paths)
  I(omega) = (1-a2)+(a1-a2)w  (Eisenstein integer)
  I(i) = (1-a2) + a1*i        (Gaussian integer)

The CHECK relation:
  I(2) = 2*I(1) + 2*a2 - 1
  H = 2*(1+a1+a2) + 2*a2 - 1 = 1 + 2*a1 + 4*a2  (correct)

  More interesting: I(2) from I(omega) and I(i)?
  I(omega): real = 1-a2, omega-coeff = a1-a2
    => a2 = 1-real, a1 = omega-coeff + (1-real)
  I(i): real = 1-a2, imag = a1
    => a2 = 1-Re(I(i)), a1 = Im(I(i))
  Then H = 1 + 2*Im(I(i)) + 4*(1 - Re(I(i)))
         = 5 - 4*Re(I(i)) + 2*Im(I(i))

Verification at n=7:
  a1= 36, a2= 6: H=97, I(1)=43, Re(I(i))=-5, Im(I(i))=36, 5-4Re+2Im=97
  a1= 37, a2= 4: H=91, I(1)=42, Re(I(i))=-3, Im(I(i))=37, 5-4Re+2Im=91
  a1= 45, a2= 6: H=115, I(1)=52, Re(I(i))=-5, Im(I(i))=45, 5-4Re+2Im=115
  a1= 28, a2= 4: H=73, I(1)=33, Re(I(i))=-3, Im(I(i))=28, 5-4Re+2Im=73
  a1= 32, a2= 4: H=81, I(1)=37, Re(I(i))=-3, Im(I(i))=32, 5-4Re+2Im=81
  a1= 25, a2= 5: H=71, I(1)=31, Re(I(i))=-4, Im(I(i))=25, 5-4Re+2Im=71
  a1= 34, a2= 6: H=93, I(1)=41, Re(I(i))=-5, Im(I(i))=34, 5-4Re+2Im=93
  a1= 30, a2= 4: H=77, I(1)=35, Re(I(i))=-3, Im(I(i))=30, 5-4Re+2Im=77

The formula H = 5 - 4*Re(I(i)) + 2*Im(I(i)) shows:
  H increases with a1 (more cycles -> more paths)
  H increases with a2 (more disjoint pairs -> more paths)
  The coefficients 4 and 2 are POWERS OF 2
  And the constant 5 = 2+3!

======================================================================
PART 8: CAYLEY-DICKSON DOUBLING AND I.P. DEGREE TRANSITION
======================================================================

I(x) = 1 + a1*x + a2*x^2 + a3*x^3 + ...
The maximum independence number alpha(Omega(T)) determines the degree.

  n <= 4: alpha(Omega) = 0 or 1, degree <= 1 (real = dim 1)
  n = 5,6,7: alpha(Omega) = 0,1, or 2, degree <= 2 (complex = dim 2)
  n = 8: alpha(Omega) can reach 3, degree <= 3
  n = 9+: alpha(Omega) can reach 4+, degree <= 4+

Cayley-Dickson parallel:
  Degree 1 (linear I.P.): R (dim 1) — fully ordered
  Degree 2 (quadratic I.P.): C (dim 2) — lose ordering
  Degree 3 (cubic I.P.): between C and H
  Degree 4 (quartic I.P.): H (dim 4) — lose commutativity

But wait: Cayley-Dickson doubles, while I.P. degree increments by 1.
The connection is through EVALUATION POINTS needed:
  Degree d polynomial needs d+1 points to determine it
  d=1: 2 points = 2^1 (complex)
  d=2: 3 points (not a power of 2!)
  d=3: 4 points = 2^2 (quaternionic)
  d=7: 8 points = 2^3 (octonionic)

  The Cayley-Dickson step at 2^k evaluations corresponds to
  I.P. degree 2^k - 1:
    2^1 - 1 = 1: linear I.P. (n <= 4)
    2^2 - 1 = 3: cubic I.P. (n = 8)
    2^3 - 1 = 7: degree-7 I.P. (n = ?)

  For degree 3 (n=8): the 4 evaluations I(1), I(2), I(omega), I(i)
  form a COMPLETE basis for recovering I(x).
  This is the 'quaternionic' level of information.
  The fact that n=8 = 2^3 matches the Cayley-Dickson dim for
  quaternion -> octonion transition is suggestive but not proven.

Estimating max alpha(Omega) at n=7 vs n=8:
  n=7: alpha(Omega) <= 2 always (proved, Omega has <= 14+21+1=36 vertices)
  n=8: alpha(Omega) can reach 3 (3 mutually disjoint odd cycles)
  Example: three 3-cycles on disjoint vertex triples
    Vertices {0,1,2}, {3,4,5}, {6,7}: only 2 triples of 3 from 8 vertices
    Wait: C(8,3)=56, can we find 3 DISJOINT 3-cycles?
    Need 9 vertices for 3 disjoint triples, but n=8 has only 8!
    So max disjoint 3-cycles at n=8 is FLOOR(8/3) = 2
    But: a 3-cycle and a 5-cycle on disjoint vertices: 3+5=8 = n!
    So alpha(Omega) >= 2 at n=8, and a1=3 = 1 disjoint 3-5 pair + 1 cycle
    Can we get 3 mutually disjoint odd cycles? No, because 3+3+3=9 > 8
    But 3+5 = 8, and we need a third cycle disjoint from both.
    That's impossible: 8 vertices are all used up!
    So alpha(Omega) = 2 at n=8 as well! (for 3-cycles and 5-cycles)

    What about at n=9? 3+3+3=9: three disjoint 3-cycles possible!
    So alpha(Omega) can reach 3 at n=9 = 3^2
    The CUBIC transition happens at n=9, not n=8!
    This matches: 9 = 3^2, and cubic I.P. = degree 3

======================================================================
PART 9: DISCRIMINANT 4*a2 - a1^2 AND PHASE TRANSITION
======================================================================

I(x) = 1 + a1*x + a2*x^2
Roots: x = (-a1 +- sqrt(a1^2 - 4*a2)) / (2*a2)
Discriminant: Delta = a1^2 - 4*a2
  Delta > 0: two real roots (hyperbolic)
  Delta = 0: double root (parabolic)
  Delta < 0: two complex roots (elliptic)

Root type distribution at n=7 (5000 samples):
  elliptic    :    0 (0.0%)
  hyperbolic  : 4272 (85.4%)
  parabolic   :    5 (0.1%)
  linear (a2=0): 723

The phase transition at Delta = 0:
  a1^2 = 4*a2 => a2 = a1^2/4
  For integer a2: a1 must be even, say a1 = 2m, then a2 = m^2
  Parabolic tournaments: (a1, a2) = (2m, m^2)
  m=0: (a1= 0, a2= 0), H=   1, N_eis=   1, double root at x = inf
  m=1: (a1= 2, a2= 1), H=   9, N_eis=   1, double root at x = -1.0000
  m=2: (a1= 4, a2= 4), H=  25, N_eis=   9, double root at x = -0.5000
  m=3: (a1= 6, a2= 9), H=  49, N_eis=  49, double root at x = -0.3333
  m=4: (a1= 8, a2=16), H=  81, N_eis= 169, double root at x = -0.2500
  m=5: (a1=10, a2=25), H= 121, N_eis= 441, double root at x = -0.2000
  m=6: (a1=12, a2=36), H= 169, N_eis= 961, double root at x = -0.1667
  m=7: (a1=14, a2=49), H= 225, N_eis=1849, double root at x = -0.1429

Achievable parabolic points at n=7:
  (a1=2, a2=1): found 3 times

  Note: for (a1, a2) = (2, 1), Delta = 4-4 = 0
  This requires exactly 2 odd cycles with 1 disjoint pair
  Two disjoint odd cycles: possible at n>=6 (e.g., 3+3=6)
  At n=6: (a1=2, a2=1) found 10/5000 times (0.2%)

======================================================================
PART 10: H MOD 8 — THE OCTONIONIC RESIDUE
======================================================================

H = 1 + 2*a1 + 4*a2
H mod 2 = 1 always
H mod 4 = 1 + 2*(a1 mod 2)
H mod 8 = 1 + 2*a1 + 4*(a2 mod 2)  (since 8|4*2)
        = 1 + 2*(a1 mod 4) + 4*(a2 mod 2)

H mod 4 distribution at n=7:
  H = 0 mod 4:    0 (0.0%)
  H = 1 mod 4: 2820 (56.4%)
  H = 2 mod 4:    0 (0.0%)
  H = 3 mod 4: 2180 (43.6%)

H mod 8 distribution at n=7:
  H = 0 mod 8:    0 (0.0%)
  H = 1 mod 8: 1495 (29.9%)
  H = 2 mod 8:    0 (0.0%)
  H = 3 mod 8: 1184 (23.7%)
  H = 4 mod 8:    0 (0.0%)
  H = 5 mod 8: 1325 (26.5%)
  H = 6 mod 8:    0 (0.0%)
  H = 7 mod 8:  996 (19.9%)

Explanation:
  H mod 8 = (1 + 2*a1 + 4*a2) mod 8
  H is always odd, so only residues 1, 3, 5, 7 appear
  H mod 4: only 1 and 3 (since H = 1 + 2*a1 mod 4)
    H = 1 mod 4 iff a1 even
    H = 3 mod 4 iff a1 odd

  H mod 8:
    1 mod 8: a1 even, a2 even
    3 mod 8: a1 odd, a2 even
    5 mod 8: a1 even, a2 odd
    7 mod 8: a1 odd, a2 odd

  H mod 8 determines (a1 mod 2, a2 mod 2)!
  This is a 2-dimensional mod-2 invariant
  = point in F_2 x F_2 = (Z/2Z)^2
  The group (Z/2Z)^2 has order 4 = 2^2 = dim(quaternions)

  Extended: H mod 16 determines (a1 mod 4, a2 mod 2)
  and H mod 32 determines (a1 mod 8, a2 mod 2)
  In general: H mod 2^k determines (a1 mod 2^(k-1), a2 mod 2^(k-2))

  2-adic structure of H-1:
  H - 1 = 2*(a1 + 2*a2)
  v_2(H-1) >= 1 always
  v_2(H-1) >= 2 iff a1 + 2*a2 even iff a1 even
  v_2(H-1) >= 3 iff a1 + 2*a2 = 0 mod 4 iff a1 = 0 mod 4

  v_2(H-1) distribution at n=7:
    v_2(H-1) = 0:   12 (0.2%)
    v_2(H-1) = 1: 2262 (45.2%)
    v_2(H-1) = 2: 1295 (25.9%)
    v_2(H-1) = 3:  669 (13.4%)
    v_2(H-1) = 4:  327 (6.5%)
    v_2(H-1) = 5:  192 (3.8%)
    v_2(H-1) = 6:  157 (3.1%)
    v_2(H-1) = 7:   86 (1.7%)

